column5: Description

No encoding/disassembling information is present. These should be removed/replaced with other instructions before we reach the encoding phase of codegen.RawFrm         - Instruction has no modrm byte. Operands are fixed registers. There may be an immediate present.
This form is for instructions that don't have any operands, so they are just a fixed opcode value, like 'leave'.
Instruction encodes a register in bits 2:0 of the opcode. No modrm byte. Opcode should be a multiple of 8 for such an instruction.
Instruction encodes a fixed constant address in the instruction without modrm byte. Basically opcodes 0xA0-0xA3
Instruction uses SI/ESI/RSI as a source memory address. LODS and OUTS.
Instruction uses DI/EDI/RDI as a destinatino memory address. Input in AL/AX/EAX/RAX for SCAS/STOS. Or DX for INS.
Instruction uses SI/ESI/RSI as a source memory address and DI/EDI/RDI as a destination memory address. MOVS and CMPS instructions.
Rare instruction that has two immediates. The first is 8-bits the second one is controlled by ImmT field.
Rare instruction that has two immediates. The first is 16-bits the second one is controlled by ImmT field.
modrm.mod!=0x3, modrm[2:0] and optional sib byte and displacement encode destination memory address. vex.vvvv is used encodes the next register, modrm[5:3] encodes destination register.
modrm.mod!=0x3, modrm[5:3] encodes destination register. if vex.vvvv is used it encodes the next register, modrm[2:0] encodes second or third source register
like MRMSrcMem, but vex.vvvv and memory operand are swapped. Rarely used.
like MRMSrcMem, but a second source register is encoded in bits [7:4] of an immediate. Memory is the 4th operand. Rarely used.
modrm.mod==0x3, with a value of 0 in modrm[5:3]. modrm[2:0] and optional sib byte and displacement encode memory address. This is almost the same as MRM0m, but the disassembler ignores modrm[5:3]
modrm.mod!=0x3, with a fixed value(0-7) in modrm[5:3]. modrm[2:0] and optional sib byte and displacement encode memory address.
modrm.mod==0x3, modrm[2:0] encodes destination register. if vex.vvvv is used encodes the next register, mrm[5:3] encodes the second or third register.
modrm.mod==0x3, modrm[5:3] encodes destination register. if vex.vvvv is used encodes the next register, mrm[2:0] encodes the second or third register.
like MRMSrcReg, but vex.vvvv and memory operand are swapped. Rarely used
like MRMSrcReg, but a second source register is encoded in bits [7:4] of an immediate. modrm[2:0] encodes the 4th operand. Rarely used
modrm.mod==0x3, with a value of 0 in modrm[5:3]. modrm[2:0] encodes a register. This is almost the same as MRM0r, but the disassembler ignores modrm[5:3]
modrm.mod==0x3, with a fixed value(0-7) in modrm[5:3]. modrm[2:0] encode a register
Instruction encodes with a fixed value in the range 0xC0-0xFF in the modrm byte. e.g. VMCALL, MONITOR. No known instructions use a fixed value in 0x00-0xBF range.
8-bits with a register encoded in bits 7:4
32-bit immediate
32-bit immediate that is sign extended to 64-bits.
Operand size isn't mode dependent
0x66 prefix required in 32-bit mode
0x66 prefix required in 16-bit mode
0x66 prefix should be ignored if present.
Address size prefix determined from memory operand registers encoded in modrm byte
Need a 0x67 prefix in 32-bit mode
Need a 0x67 prefix in 16-bit mode or 64-bit mode
Marks the 64-bit version of AdSize16/32 instructions.
No prefix
Doesn't encode with a prefix, but 0x66/0xf2/0xf3 prefix are different instructions to the disassembler. Sets VEX.PP=0 for VEX encoding.
Always uses a 0x66 prefix. VEX.PP=1 for VEX encoding.
Always uses a 0xF3 prefix. VEX.PP=2 for VEX encoding.
Always uses a 0xF2 prefix. VEX.PP=3 for VEX encoding.
One byte opcode. Not used by any VEX encoded instructions.
Two byte opcode, first byte is 0x0F. VEX.mmmmm=0x1 for VEX encoding.
Three byte opcode, first bytes are 0x0F 0x38. VEX.mmmmm=0x2 for VEX encoding.
Three byte opcode, first bytes are 0x0F 0x3A. VEX.mmmmm=0x3 for VEX encoding.
Used by AMD xop encoding. XOP.mmmmm=0x8
Used by AMD xop encoding. XOP.mmmmm=0x9
Used by AMD xop encoding. XOP.mmmmm=0xA
3DNow opcode map. First two bytes are 0x0F 0x0F. Opcode placed at the end of the instruction after modrm.
Oldest encoding system using opcodes and various prefix bytes.
VEX encoding introduced with AVX. First byte is 0xC4 or 0xC5. Various values encoded in bit fields of next two or three bytes before opcode and modrm.
AMD XOP encoding. Similar to VEX. First byte is 0x8F.
EVEX encoding instroduced with AVX512. First byte is 0x62. Various values encoded in bit fields of next 3 bytes before before opcode and modrm.

MMX instructions with TB prefix valid only in 64 bit mode.
